{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568485"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:16:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:16:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.8,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13796"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108262"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13796"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90663"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1879"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2979"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11545"},{"type":"tags","id":"11552"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40342"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40405"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108262","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108262"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is evacuated from Thailand after recent flooding and presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of watery, greasy diarrhoea, abdominal cramping, and fatigue. She has a medical history of systemic lupus erythematosus for which she takes prednisolone and hydroxychloroquine. She also has seasonal hayfever. She was travelling with a tour group of 20 people who were staying at a local guesthouse where the water supply was disrupted following recent flooding. She mentions that several other tourists have similar symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 121/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft with mild generalised tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management after notifying the public health authorities?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recommend oral probiotics","Ciprofloxacin for three days","Metronidazole and oral rehydration","Paromomycin for seven days","Wait for public health investigation before starting treatment"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a potential outbreak of giardiasis among tourists from Thailand following flooding that disrupted the water supply. Multiple cases among travellers suggest contaminated water sources, representing a significant public health concern requiring immediate action. \u003Cem\u003EGiardia intestinalis\u003C/em\u003E is transmitted by faecal-oral route or drinking contaminated water sources causing diarrhoea, foul smelling greasy stools and malaise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole and oral rehydration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step after public health notification. While the outbreak investigation proceeds, individual cases still require prompt treatment to reduce symptoms and prevent further transmission. Metronidazole is a well-established treatment for giardiasis for symptomatic patients, typically given for five days. Combined with oral rehydration therapy, this approach addresses both the parasitic infection and the fluid losses from diarrhoea. This is particularly important in an immunocompromised patient with systemic lupus erythematosus on immunosuppressive medications, as she is at higher risk for more severe or prolonged infection and dehydration. Tinidazole is an alternative to metronidazole but it has been discontinued in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend oral probiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as the primary treatment for giardiasis. While probiotics may have a role in restoring gut flora after treatment, they do not have antiparasitic activity against \u003Cem\u003EGiardia\u003C/em\u003E. The patient requires specific antimicrobial therapy to eradicate the parasite, not just symptomatic management. Delaying appropriate treatment could lead to prolonged symptoms and continued transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin for three days\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it is not effective against \u003Cem\u003EGiardia\u003C/em\u003E. Fluoroquinolones are typically used for bacterial causes of gastroenteritis such as traveller\u0027s diarrhoea caused by enterotoxigenic \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, but would not treat this parasitic infection. The clinical picture of greasy, watery diarrhoea is more consistent with giardiasis than bacterial gastroenteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParomomycin for seven days\u003C/strong\u003E is an aminoglycoside antibiotic with antiparasitic activity that can be used to treat giardiasis. While it has been used as an alternative treatment in pregnancy, particularly in the first trimester, where metronidazole was traditionally avoided, current evidence supports metronidazole as first-line therapy in most patients. In this non-pregnant patient, metronidazole or tinidazole remains the preferred treatment due to its established efficacy and oral bioavailability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWait for public health investigation\u003C/strong\u003E before starting treatment would unnecessarily delay care for the individual patient. Treatment can proceed concurrently with the public health response, which is particularly important for this immunocompromised patient who may be at risk for more severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of the ABCD approach as per Royal Australian College of General Practitioners to avoiding traveller\u0027s diarrhoea: A) Avoid anything that may be contaminated with faecal material, particularly water and food; B) Bottled water is the safest option, with attention to intact seals; C) Clean hands thoroughly with alcohol-based cleansers and cover feet to prevent soil-transmitted infections; D) Disease risk is higher in immunocompromised individuals who should take extra precautions and inform healthcare providers of their status when becoming unwell.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ABCD approach to avoiding traveller\u0027s diarrhoea includes: Avoid contaminated food/water, Bottled water is safest, Clean hands and Cover feet, Disease risk is higher in immunocompromised individuals.","Public health notification is mandatory for suspected outbreaks of giardiasis to enable source identification and prevent further transmission.","Treatment with metronidazole for five days combined with oral rehydration therapy is appropriate for symptomatic giardiasis, particularly in immunocompromised patients."],"references":["Slack A, Parasitic causes of prolonged diarrhoea in travellers Diagnosis and management. Australian Family Practice. 2012: 41 (10). Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/october/parasitic-causes-of-prolonged-diarrhoea-in-travell","Giardia intestinalis infection (giardiasis). Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines. [cited 2025 Mar 10]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90663"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90663"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T20:41:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T20:53:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13796"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108262"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags